Data processing for individual network

Nguyen Huynh

17 December 2021

Abstract

This script depicts the differential expression analysis with removal of unwanted variation. Subsequently, the importance of covariates to sample variation was evaluated, and significant covariates were then used for identification of prioritized modules. Here, we show the procedure for one representative network (Astrocyte HD). However, the same procedure was applied for all other networks.

PART 1: Differential expression analysis

Data import

# List of ENSEMBL gene ID and corresponding gene names - data curated from ENSEMBL
name2id <- read.table("data/hs95_name2ID.txt", header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
# Differential expression test 
cond1 <- "ESC_derived_CTR_Astro" # CTR samples
cond2 <- "HD_Astro" # Treatment samples

# Read in data
sampleParent <- read.table("data/sampleTable.txt", stringsAsFactors = FALSE, na.strings = "NA")
covParent <- read.table("data/covTable.txt", header = TRUE)
countParent <- read.table("data/deSeq2_RawCounts.txt")
# Genes after the filtering step
keep <- readLines("data/keepGenes.txt")

Sample selection

# sampleData clean-up ----------------------------------------------------------
sample <- row.names(sampleParent)[c(which(sampleParent$condition == cond1), which(sampleParent$condition == cond2))]
sampleData <- sampleParent[sample,]
### Only get the colnames (covariate) of investigating variances. 
sampleData <- sampleData[, which(covParent$take_nottake==1), drop = FALSE]
sampleData$condition <- factor(sampleData$condition, levels=c(cond1, cond2))

# countData clean-up -----------------------------------------------------------
countData <- countParent[, row.names(sampleData)]

# covData clean-up -------------------------------------------------------------
# take_nottake: 0: do not consider; 1: consider 
# type        : 1: categorical; 2: continuous 
covData <- covParent[which(covParent$take_nottake==1),]

Test: HD_Astro vs ESC_derived_CTR_Astro

if (!all.equal(colnames(sampleData), as.character(covData$covariate))) {
  cat("Error: Check sampleData and covData. They do not have the same covariate strings.")
}

if (!all.equal(colnames(countData), row.names(sampleData))) {
  cat("Error: Check countData and sampleData. They do not have the same column names and row names")
} else {
    # Make DESeq object 
    dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData=countData, colData=sampleData, design= ~ condition)
    dds <- DESeq(dds, parallel=FALSE)
} #-End else

DESeq2 First-Pass

DESeq2 was used to perform data normalization and differential expression analysis on each set of raw expression measures. This is the first pass to create a set of genes whose expressions were not differentially expressed between 2 investigated groups. These genes, referred to as empirical control genes, are then used for downstream RUVseq analysis (Removal of Unwanted Variation).

res1 <- callDiff(cond2, cond1, dds)
res1 <- as.data.frame(res1)
res1 <- res1[order(res1$padj), ]
# Get negative genes for empirical control. In this case we want those genes whose padj values are more than 0.75
empirical <- row.names(res1)[which(res1$padj > 0.75)]

The number of empirical control genes used in this experiment is: 2067

RUVs

# Upper quartile normalization
set <- betweenLaneNormalization(as.matrix(countData), which="upper")
differences <- makeGroups(sampleData$condition)

Pick K

tmp.df <- data.frame(K=character(), Variation = numeric(), logP = numeric())
# Loop through the first 30 Ks
for (i in 1:30) {
  tmp <- RUVs(set, empirical, k=i, differences)
  tmp.pcov <- run_pca(tmp$normalizedCounts)
  tmp.pcaRes <- prcomp(t(log2(tmp$normalizedCounts+1)))
  tmp.eigs <- tmp.pcaRes$sdev^2
  tmp.perc <- tmp.eigs[1]/sum(tmp.eigs)*100
  tmp <- data.frame(K=i, Variation = tmp.perc, logP = tmp.pcov[1,4])
  tmp.df <- rbind(tmp.df, tmp)
}
# Picked K is the first significant K (p < 0.05) that could explain more than 20% of sample variation
KK <- 3
p1 <- ggplot(tmp.df, aes(x=K, y = Variation)) + geom_line() + geom_vline(xintercept = KK, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") + geom_hline(yintercept= 20, linetype= "dotted") +theme_bw() + theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(), axis.title.x = element_blank())
breakers <- unique(c(1,5,10,15,20,25,30,KK))
p2 <- ggplot(tmp.df, aes(x=K, y = logP)) + geom_line() + geom_vline(xintercept = KK, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") + scale_x_continuous(breaks = breakers) + theme_bw() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(color=ifelse(breakers == KK, "red", "black")))
cowplot::plot_grid(p1, p2, ncol = 1) 

# Predetermined K from the above for loop 
setG <- RUVs(set, empirical, k=KK, differences)

Data Visualization Before and After RUVSeq

PCA Plot: The plot of principal components (PC). PC1 and PC2 are the two components explaining most of the variance. This plot is useful for visualizing the overall effect of experimental covariates and batch effects. PCA plots were computed on log2-transformed data.

COUNT <- list(as.matrix(countData), set, counts(dds, normalize=TRUE), setG$normalizedCounts)
names(COUNT) <- c("NN", "UQ", "DESeq", "RUV")

logCOUNT <- lapply(COUNT, function(x) log2(x+1))
pcaRes <- lapply(logCOUNT, function(x) prcomp(t(x)))
pcaCoord <- lapply(pcaRes, function(x) x$x)
eigs <- lapply(pcaRes, function(x) x$sdev^2)
percentage <- lapply(eigs, function(x) c(x[1]/sum(x), x[2]/sum(x)))
percentage <- lapply(percentage, function(x) round(x*100, 1))
percentage <- lapply(percentage, function(x) paste0("(",x, "%)"))
# Define colors
col_val <- c("grey70", "mediumblue")
names(col_val) <- c(cond1, cond2)

p1 <- plotexplorer(pcaCoord[[1]], "Raw Data", percentage[[1]]) + scale_color_manual(values = col_val) + scale_fill_manual(values = col_val)
p2 <- plotexplorer(pcaCoord[[2]], "Upper Quartile", percentage[[2]]) + scale_color_manual(values = col_val) + scale_fill_manual(values = col_val)
p3 <- plotexplorer(pcaCoord[[3]], "DESeq2", percentage[[3]]) + scale_color_manual(values = col_val) + scale_fill_manual(values = col_val)
p4 <- plotexplorer(pcaCoord[[4]], "RUVs", percentage[[4]]) + scale_color_manual(values = col_val) + scale_fill_manual(values = col_val)
cowplot::plot_grid(p1, p2, p3, p4, ncol=2)

DESeq2 Second-Pass 

sampleDataW <-cbind(sampleData, setG$W)
ddsW <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = countData, colData = sampleDataW, design = ~ condition)

### compile formula for DESeq2 based on number of K:
      form_string <- ""
      for (w in 1:KK) {
        if (w == KK) {
          form_string <- paste(form_string, "W_", w, sep = "")
        } else {
          form_string <- paste(form_string, "W_", w, " + ", sep = "")
        } # end else
      } # end for
      
      design(ddsW) <- formula(paste("~", form_string, " + condition", sep = ""))

ddsW <- DESeq(ddsW, parallel = FALSE)
res <- callDiff(cond2, cond1, ddsW)

res$geneName <- plyr::mapvalues(row.names(res), name2id$ensembl_gene_id, name2id$external_gene_name, warn_missing = FALSE)

PART 2: WGCNA

An ensemble of all samples were considered for batch correction before WGCNA on each individual network

dds_all <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = countParent, colData = sampleParent, design= ~ condition)
sf <- estimateSizeFactorsForMatrix(counts(dds_all))
sizeFactors(dds_all) <- sf
# Transform data 
vst_all <- varianceStabilizingTransformation(dds_all)
# 
sampleParent$condition3 <- sampleParent$condition
sampleParent$condition3[sampleParent$condition3 %in% c("iPSC_derived_CTR", "ESC_derived_CTR")] <- "CTR"
sampleParent$condition3[sampleParent$condition3 %in% c("iPSC_derived_CTR_Astro", "ESC_derived_CTR_Astro")] <- "CTR_Astro"
vst_corrected2 <- vst_all
# Remove batch effect & make into WGCNA-compatible matrix 
data <- removeBatchEffect(assay(vst_corrected2), batch = sampleParent$study_id, design = model.matrix(~sampleParent$condition3))
# Save for later network preservation 
saveRDS(data, "./results/batch_corrected.RDS")
mat <- t(data)

TOM

# Pick power 
power <- 11
# Calculate TOM
TOM <- TOMsimilarityFromExpr(datExpr = subset, networkType = "signed", TOMType = "signed", power = power, corType = "bicor", maxPOutliers = 0.1)
## TOM calculation: adjacency..
## ..will not use multithreading.
##  Fraction of slow calculations: 0.000000
## ..connectivity..
## ..matrix multiplication (system BLAS)..
## ..normalization..
## ..done.
# Save for later calculation 
saveRDS(TOM,"./results/Astrocyte_HD/TOM.RDS")
dissTOM <- 1 - TOM
# Create modules of genes by average linkage hierachical clustering based on dissimilarity between genes
geneTree <- hclust(as.dist(dissTOM), method = "average")
modules <-
  cutreeDynamic(
    dendro = geneTree,
    distM = dissTOM,
    deepSplit = 1,
    pamRespectsDendro = FALSE,
    minClusterSize = 50
  )
##  ..cutHeight not given, setting it to 0.992  ===>  99% of the (truncated) height range in dendro.
##  ..done.
moduleColors <- labels2colors(modules)
plotDendroAndColors(
  geneTree,
  moduleColors,
  "Module Colors",
  dendroLabels = FALSE,
  hang = 0.01,
  addGuide = TRUE,
  guideHang = 0.05,
  main = "Cluster Dendrogram"
)

MEList <- moduleEigengenes(subset, colors = moduleColors)
MEs <- MEList$eigengenes
df <- data.frame(geneID=colnames(subset), moduleColor = moduleColors)
df$geneName <- plyr::mapvalues(df$geneID, name2id$ensembl_gene_id, name2id$external_gene_name, warn_missing = F)
write.table(df, "./results/Astrocyte_HD/geneModuleMembership.txt", row.names = F, col.names = T, quote = F, sep = "\t")
write.table(as.data.frame(MEs), "./results/Astrocyte_HD/ModuleEigengene.txt", row.names = T, col.names = NA, quote = F, sep = "\t")
